The paper deals with the problem of private learning, which is a subfield of machine learning and privacy-preserving data analysis. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely category. The paper also involves differential privacy, which is a common technique for privacy-preserving data analysis, and hence cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) is also a likely category. The paper uses combinatorial techniques to characterize the sample complexity of private learning, which suggests that it may also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also mentions optimization problems and private data release, which are relevant to cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), respectively.
